  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are international laws and frameworks aimed at combating money laundering. These laws and frameworks have been established to prevent and combat the practice of disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by means of transfers involving foreign banks or legitimate businesses.\n\nOne of the most significant international frameworks is the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**, which was established in 1989. The FATF sets international standards for combating money laundering, terrorist financing, and other related threats to the integrity of the international financial system. The FATF's **40 Recommendations** provide a comprehensive and consistent framework of measures which countries should implement in order to combat money laundering and terrorist financing.\n\nAdditionally, the **United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances** (1988), also known as the **Vienna Convention**, was one of the first international treaties to address money laundering. It requires signatory countries to criminalize the laundering of proceeds from drug trafficking and to implement measures to combat it.\n\nThe **United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime** (2000), also known as the **Palermo Convention**, further expanded the scope to include the laundering of proceeds from all serious crimes, not just drug trafficking. It obliges signatory states to establish money laundering as a criminal offence and to implement measures to detect, prevent, and punish money laundering activities.\n\nOther regional bodies and agreements also contribute to the fight against money laundering. For example:\n\n1. **The European Union (EU)**: The EU has several directives aimed at preventing money laundering and terrorist financing, such as the **Anti-Money Laundering Directive (AMLD)**, which has been updated several times to strengthen measures against money laundering.\n\n2. **The Council of Europe Convention on Laundering, Search, Seizure and Confiscation of the Proceeds from Crime and on the Financing of Terrorism (Warsaw Convention, 2005)**: This convention provides a comprehensive legal framework for international cooperation in preventing and combating money laundering and the financing of terrorism.\n\n3. **The Basel Committee on Banking Supervision**: This committee has issued guidelines for banks to establish effective anti-money laundering (AML) measures, including customer due diligence (CDD) and reporting of suspicious transactions.\n\nCountries around the world have adopted these international standards and have enacted their own domestic laws and regulations to combat money laundering. These laws typically require financial institutions to implement robust AML programs, report suspicious transactions to relevant authorities, and maintain records of financial transactions.\n\nOverall, the international community recognizes the importance of combating money laundering to maintain the integrity of the global financial system and has established a network of laws and cooperative mechanisms to address this issue.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
